# Second pass and clarity rewrite

You have just completed an initial Blue Team audit. Before the report is saved, do one
second pass. The goal is not cosmetic editing; it is to catch important methodology
problems the first pass may have missed and then make the final findings easy
for an outside researcher to understand.

First, re-read your current findings and the artifacts you inspected. Then do a targeted
coverage check over the main result:

1. Identify the main claim and the exact code/results path that produces it.
2. Inspect the training setup behind that claim: how examples become model inputs
   and targets, which parts of each example affect the objective, and whether information is
   included, excluded, supplied, filtered, or weighted in a non-obvious way.
3. Inspect the evaluation setup: prompts, context supplied to the model, judges,
   filtering, sampled records, controls, baselines, seeds, uncertainty, and aggregation code.
4. Check transcripts or later write-ups where needed to determine whether a possible issue
   was fixed, superseded, or still affects the final report.
5. Check the strongest negative, null, or limiting results, because they often determine
   whether the headline claim is too broad.

Do not spawn sub-agents or independent reviewer agents in this pass. Keep the check focused
on the existing evidence and only the extra artifacts needed to resolve coverage gaps.

Check whether the result is framed as one setting but the code implements a different one:
a different objective, different target, extra supplied
context, filtered conditions, weighted examples, or a required evaluation condition the
report does not make clear. If that changes the meaning of the reported metric, comparison,
main result, or threat model, add a finding.

Now produce the final saved report. This is the version a researcher will skim, so edit
aggressively for speed and clarity:

- Keep findings that remain real and result-affecting.
- Add any important concern you found in this second pass.
- Drop or downgrade a concern only if the evidence shows it was fixed, superseded, or not
  result-affecting.
- Drop any finding if, after this pass, you are below 50% sure it is a genuine
  result-affecting issue. Use 50-60 confidence only for concerns that are real enough for a
  reviewer to check but still meaningfully uncertain.
- Do not collapse distinct concerns just because they affect the same headline. A weak
  baseline, extra information given to one condition, low statistical power, post-hoc
  filtering, and overbroad framing are separate findings when they would change trust for
  different reasons.
- Rewrite every finding so a researcher who has not read this project can understand it.
  Define project-specific terms, explain what the relevant artifact is before saying what is
  wrong with it, and make the causal chain to the affected number or takeaway explicit.
- For comparison failures, use plain contrast language: say what the report compared, what
  one side was allowed to see or use, what the other side had to do without, and what a
  reader would wrongly infer from the headline. In `mechanism`, say what the reader would
  wrongly believe if they trusted the original headline or number.
- Apply this skim test to every finding before saving it:
  - the title names the concrete problem, not just a theme;
  - the title is at most 18 words, preferably 14 or fewer, and contains no acronyms or
    project shorthand because the UI shows titles by themselves;
  - `context` has exactly two short paragraphs: first the relevant claim/result, then the
    key setup/evidence needed to judge the concern;
  - neither context paragraph is a one-sentence stub; each should usually be 45-90 words
    and must have at least two sentences;
  - before saving the final JSON, count sentences in each context paragraph; if a paragraph
    has one sentence, add a second plain sentence explaining why the claim matters or what
    evidence points to the problem;
  - `issue` states the concrete problem directly, without repeating all the background, and
    should usually be 45-95 words;
  - `mechanism` is the "Why it matters" section and starts with the affected claim, number,
    or takeaway, then says what a skimming reader would get wrong in 2-3 short sentences
    and at least 45 words;
  - acronyms and run-internal labels are defined in plain words or moved to `location`;
  - audit-process jargon such as "affordance", "contract", "reader-facing", "topline",
    and "provenance" is replaced with ordinary wording;
  - no sentence is doing three jobs at once;
  - internal run names appear only in `location` unless immediately explained.

Output the same format as before: a brief plain-text orientation, then a single ```json
findings block with exactly the same schema (`title`, `concern`, `location`, `context`,
`issue`, `mechanism`, `confidence`). This block replaces the earlier one and is the version
that will be saved and shown.
